<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
<subsection xml:id="anovamodel">
    <title>The model for the data and the meaning of <m>F</m></title>

    <p>At a fundamental level, ANOVA is a competition between two different statistical models, <m><![CDATA[H_0]]></m> and <m><![CDATA[H_1]]></m>. When I described the null and alternative hypotheses at the start of the section, I was a little imprecise about what these models actually are. I'll remedy that now, though you probably won't like me for doing so. If you recall, our null hypothesis was that all of the group means are identical to one another. If so, then a natural way to think about the outcome variable <m><![CDATA[Y_{ik}]]></m> is to describe individual scores in terms of a single population mean <m><![CDATA[\mu]]></m>, plus the deviation from that population mean. This deviation is usually denoted <m><![CDATA[\epsilon_{ik}]]></m> and is traditionally called the <em>error</em> or <em>residual</em> associated with that observation. Be careful though: just like we saw with the word "significant", the word "error" has a technical meaning in statistics that isn't quite the same as its everyday English definition. In everyday language, "error" implies a mistake of some kind; in statistics, it doesn't (or at least, not necessarily). With that in mind, the word "residual" is a better term than the word "error". In statistics, both words mean "leftover variability": that is, "stuff" that the model can't explain. In any case, here's what the null hypothesis looks like when we write it as a statistical model:</p>
    <me><![CDATA[Y_{ik} = \mu + \epsilon_{ik}]]></me>
    <p>where we make the <em>assumption</em> (discussed later) that the residual values <m><![CDATA[\epsilon_{ik}]]></m> are normally distributed, with mean 0 and a standard deviation <m><![CDATA[\sigma]]></m> that is the same for all groups. To use the notation that we introduced in <xref ref="probability"/> we would write this assumption like this:</p>
    <me><![CDATA[\epsilon_{ik} \sim \mbox{Normal}(0, \sigma^2)]]></me>
    <p>What about the alternative hypothesis, <m><![CDATA[H_1]]></m>? The only difference between the null hypothesis and the alternative hypothesis is that we allow each group to have a different population mean. So, if we let <m><![CDATA[\mu_k]]></m> denote the population mean for the <m><![CDATA[k]]></m>-th group in our experiment, then the statistical model corresponding to <m><![CDATA[H_1]]></m> is:</p>
    <me><![CDATA[Y_{ik} = \mu_k + \epsilon_{ik}]]></me>
    <p>where, once again, we assume that the error terms are normally distributed with mean 0 and standard deviation <m><![CDATA[\sigma]]></m>. That is, the alternative hypothesis also assumes that</p>
    <me><![CDATA[\epsilon \sim \mbox{Normal}(0, \sigma^2)]]></me>
    <p>Okay, now that we've described the statistical models underpinning <m><![CDATA[H_0]]></m> and <m><![CDATA[H_1]]></m> in more detail, it's now pretty straightforward to say what the mean square values are measuring, and what this means for the interpretation of <m><![CDATA[F]]></m>. I won't bore you with the proof of this, but it turns out that the within-groups mean square, <m><![CDATA[\mbox{MS}_w]]></m>, can be viewed as an estimator (in the technical sense: <xref ref="estimation"/>) of the error variance <m><![CDATA[\sigma^2]]></m>. The between-groups mean square <m><![CDATA[\mbox{MS}_b]]></m> is also an estimator; but what it estimates is the error variance <em>plus</em> a quantity that depends on the true differences among the group means. If we call this quantity <m><![CDATA[Q]]></m>, then we can see that the <m><![CDATA[F]]></m>-statistic is basically<fn>In a later versions I'm intending to expand on this. But because I'm writing in a rush, and am already over my deadlines, I'll just briefly note that if you read ahead to <xref ref="anova2"/> and look at how the "treatment effect" at level <m><![CDATA[k]]></m> of a factor is defined in terms of the <m><![CDATA[\alpha_k]]></m> values (see <xref ref="interactions"/>), it turns out that <m><![CDATA[Q]]></m> refers to a weighted mean of the squared treatment effects, <m><![CDATA[Q=(\sum_{k=1}^G N_k\alpha_k^2)/(G-1)]]></m>.</fn></p>
    <me><![CDATA[F = \frac{\hat{Q} + \hat\sigma^2}{\hat\sigma^2}]]></me>
    <p>where the true value <m><![CDATA[Q=0]]></m> if the null hypothesis is true, and <m><![CDATA[Q > 0]]></m> if the alternative hypothesis is true (e.g. ch. 10 <xref ref="biblio-Hays1994">Hays, 1994</xref>). Therefore, at a bare minimum <em>the <m><![CDATA[F]]></m> value must be larger than 1</em> to have any chance of rejecting the null hypothesis. Note that this <em>doesn't</em> mean that it's impossible to get an <m><![CDATA[F]]></m>-value less than 1. What it means is that, if the null hypothesis is true the sampling distribution of the <m><![CDATA[F]]></m> ratio has a mean of 1,<fn>Or, if we want to be sticklers for accuracy, <m><![CDATA[1 + \frac{2}{df_2 - 2}]]></m>.</fn> and so we need to see <m><![CDATA[F]]></m>-values larger than 1 in order to safely reject the null.</p>
    <p>To be a bit more precise about the sampling distribution, notice that if the null hypothesis is true, both MS<m><![CDATA[_b]]></m> and MS<m><![CDATA[_w]]></m> are estimators of the variance of the residuals <m><![CDATA[\epsilon_{ik}]]></m>. If those residuals are normally distributed, then you might suspect that the estimate of the variance of <m><![CDATA[\epsilon_{ik}]]></m> is chi-square distributed... because (as discussed in <xref ref="otherdists"/> that's what a chi-square distribution <em>is</em>: it's what you get when you square a bunch of normally-distributed things and add them up. And since the <m><![CDATA[F]]></m> distribution is (again, by definition) what you get when you take the ratio between two things that are <m><![CDATA[\chi^2]]></m> distributed... we have our sampling distribution. Obviously, I'm glossing over a whole lot of stuff when I say this, but in broad terms, this really is where our sampling distribution comes from.</p>
</subsection>
